body:
the wheel gets placed in the build directory, under dist.  e.g. build/Linux/Release/dist

you can create a conda environment and install each package separately. installing both will create a conflict.

alternatively, you can just install onnxruntime-gpu-tensorrt and use the new session.set_providers() api to force execution on CPU.

e.g.
```
import onnxruntime as ort
sess = ort.InferenceSession('model.onnx')
# see what providers are enabled by default
# e.g. ['TensorrtExecutionProvider', 'CUDAExecutionProvider', 'CPUExecutionProvider'] ordered by priority
sess.get_providers()
# override and set to CPU
sess.set_providers(['CPUExecutionProvider'])
sess.run(...)
```

It seems python not generates well.

    sess = rt.InferenceSession(model_p)
AttributeError: module 'onnxruntime' has no attribute 'InferenceSession'

did you run python in the onnxruntime source directory? that may be the cause of your error if it's trying to import onnxruntime from the wrong location.
please change to a different directory and start python again.
What is this 'onnxruntime-gpu-tensorrt', I don't see it mentioned anywhere except this thread...
It's onnxruntime build from source which enables TensorRT and GPU.
